1. Handling Exceptions Globally with @RestControllerAdvice and @ExceptionHandler

Theory

(i) @RestControllerAdvice is a special Spring annotation that allows you to handle exceptions
across your whole application in one place (global error handling).
(ii) @ExceptionHandler is used inside a controller or advice class to specify which method
should handle a particular exception type.

Implementation
Global Exception Handler Example:

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    // Handle a specific exception (e.g., resource not found)
    @ExceptionHandler(ResourceNotFoundException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleResourceNotFound(ResourceNotFoundException ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND).body(ex.getMessage());
    }

    // Handle all other exceptions
    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<String> handleAllExceptions(Exception ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR)
                             .body("An unexpected error occurred: " + ex.getMessage());
    }
}


How it works:

(i) If any controller throws a ResourceNotFoundException, the first handler returns a 404
status and the exception message.
(ii) Any other unhandled exception returns a 500 status and a generic error message.


2. Validating Request Bodies and Handling Validation Exceptions Using @Valid

Theory
(i) @Valid is used to trigger validation on request bodies (DTOs or entities) based on annotations
like @NotNull, @Size, etc.
(ii) If validation fails, Spring throws a MethodArgumentNotValidException.

Implementation
DTO with Validation Annotations:

public class UserDTO {
    @NotBlank(message = "Name is required")
    private String name;

    @Email(message = "Email should be valid")
    private String email;
    // getters and setters
}

Controller:

@PostMapping("/users")
public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@Valid @RequestBody UserDTO userDTO) {
    // If validation fails, exception is thrown before this line
    User user = new User(userDTO.getName(), userDTO.getEmail());
    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(user);
}

Handling Validation Errors Globally:

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    @ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<Map<String, String>> handleValidationExceptions(MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {
        Map<String, String> errors = new HashMap<>();
        ex.getBindingResult().getFieldErrors().forEach(error ->
            errors.put(error.getField(), error.getDefaultMessage())
        );
        return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(errors); // 400 Bad Request
    }
}

How it works:

If the client sends invalid data, Spring returns a 400 Bad Request with details about which
fields failed validation.

3. Returning Proper HTTP Status Codes (404, 400, 500) for Error Scenarios

Theory
404 Not Found: Resource doesn’t exist (e.g., user not found).
400 Bad Request: Client sent invalid data (e.g., validation failed).
500 Internal Server Error: Unexpected server error.

Implementation
Throwing Custom Exceptions in Controller:

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
    User user = userRepository.findById(id)
        .orElseThrow(() -> new ResourceNotFoundException("User not found with id " + id));
    return ResponseEntity.ok(user);
}

Custom Exception:

public class ResourceNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    public ResourceNotFoundException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}

Handled by GlobalExceptionHandler (see above), which returns 404.

4. Summary Table

Scenario	          Exception/Annotation	              HTTP Status	Example Handler Method

Resource not found	  Custom Exception + @ExceptionHandler	 404	    handleResourceNotFound
Validation failed	  @Valid + @ExceptionHandler	         400	    handleValidationExceptions
Unexpected error	  Exception + @ExceptionHandler	         500	    handleAllExceptions


Q.What happens if I don't give valid annotation?

1. Without @Valid

@PostMapping("/users")
public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody UserDTO userDTO) {
    // No @Valid here
    User user = new User(userDTO.getName(), userDTO.getEmail());
    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(user);
}

What happens:
(i)   Validation annotations (like @NotBlank, @Email) on your UserDTO fields are ignored.
(ii)  Spring does NOT automatically check if the incoming data is valid.
(iii) If the client sends invalid data (e.g., empty name, invalid email), the method will
      still execute, and you may save invalid data to your database.
(iv) No validation exception is thrown by Spring.


2. With @Valid

@PostMapping("/users")
public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@Valid @RequestBody UserDTO userDTO) {
    // Validation is triggered here
    User user = new User(userDTO.getName(), userDTO.getEmail());
    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(user);
}

What happens:

(i)   Spring checks all validation annotations on UserDTO.
(ii)  If any field is invalid, Spring throws a MethodArgumentNotValidException before your
      method body runs.
(iii) You can handle this exception globally (e.g., with @RestControllerAdvice) to return a
      400 Bad Request and error details.


3. Summary Table

With @Valid                                       	Without @Valid

Validation runs	                                    No validation
Invalid data rejected (400)	                        Invalid data accepted
Exception thrown on invalid input	                No exception, method runs


In short:

(i)  Without @Valid, validation is skipped and invalid data can be processed or saved.
(ii) With @Valid, Spring checks the data and rejects invalid input with a 400 error [1] [2].